Piece of mineral crystal used to make jewelry

Several terms redirect here. For other uses, see [Gemstone (disambiguation)](/Gemstone_(disambiguation)), [Gems (disambiguation)](/Gems_(disambiguation)), [Gem (disambiguation)](/Gem_(disambiguation)), [Jewels (disambiguation)](/Jewels_(disambiguation)), and [Precious stone (disambiguation)](/Precious_stone_(disambiguation)).

Group of precious and semiprecious stones—both uncut and faceted—including (clockwise from top left) [diamond](/Diamond), uncut synthetic [sapphire](/Sapphire), [ruby](/Ruby), uncut [emerald](/Emerald), and [amethyst](/Amethyst) crystal cluster.

A gemstone, a term burdened with various synonyms such as "fine gem," "jewel," "precious stone," or the rather dismissive "semiprecious stone," is, at its most fundamental, a segment of [mineral](/Mineral) [crystal](/Crystal). Its purpose? To be meticulously cut and polished, transforming it from a mere geological curiosity into an object of human desire, primarily for [jewelry](/Jewellery) or other superficial [adornments](/Adornment). It seems even the most stoic geological formations aren't safe from human vanity.

However, the definition, much like human intentions, isn't always as clear-cut as one might hope. Certain [rocks](/Rock_(geology)), despite their less crystalline origins—think the deep azure of [lapis lazuli](/Lapis_lazuli), the iridescent mystery of [opal](/Opal), or the sharp, volcanic glass of [obsidian](/Obsidian)—find themselves lumped into this category. And then there are the truly unconventional: materials of [organic](/Organic_chemistry) provenance, entirely devoid of mineral status, yet deemed worthy of adornment. This curious collection includes the fossilized tree resin known as [amber](/Amber), the dense, coal-like [jet](/Jet_(gemstone)), and the biologically formed [pearl](/Pearl). These are, against all mineralogical logic, frequently elevated to the status of "gemstones" due to their aesthetic appeal to the species that covets them.

While most materials deemed worthy of such distinction possess a significant degree of intrinsic hardness—a practical trait, one might argue, for something destined to be knocked about on a human appendage—this, too, is not an absolute rule. Occasionally, softer minerals, such as the vibrant [brazilianite](/Brazilianite), manage to slip through the cracks and find their way into jewelry. Their inclusion is typically predicated on exceptional color, an alluring [luster](/Lustre_(mineralogy)), or other unique physical properties that manage to capture the elusive concept of [aesthetic value](/Aesthetic_value). Yet, one must concede, the general consensus—and indeed, common sense—leans towards durability. Minerals lacking sufficient hardness, prone to brittleness and a general inability to withstand the rigors of existence (much like many of you), are rarely considered suitable for the enduring allure of a gemstone.

The global fascination with these glittering fragments is, predictably, a lucrative affair. The colored gemstone market—that is, everything beyond the ubiquitous [diamond](/Diamond)—was last assessed at a rather substantial US$1.55 billion in 2023. And, in a testament to humanity's unwavering pursuit of sparkle, this figure is projected to inflate steadily, reaching an estimated US$4.46 billion by 2033. A robust economy built on geological glitter, truly a marvel of human priorities.

Those who dedicate their lives to deciphering the secrets of these stones are known as [gemologists](/Gemology), a title that suggests a certain academic gravitas. The artisans who transform rough stone into polished beauty are called [lapidarists](/Lapidarist) or, more simply, [gemcutters](/Gemcutter). And for those who specialize in the relentless shaping of diamonds, a distinct term exists: the [diamantaire](/Diamantaire). Each title, a small testament to the specialized obsessions of humankind.

## Characteristics and classification

A [collection](/Mineral_collecting) of gemstone [pebbles](/Pebble) made by [tumbling](/Tumble_finishing) the rough stones, except the ruby and [tourmaline](/Tourmaline), with [abrasive](/Abrasive) grit inside a rotating barrel. The largest pebble here is 40 mm (1.6 in) long.

The antiquated Western classification, tracing its roots back to the [ancient Greeks](/Ancient_Greece) and their rather simplistic worldview, established a rigid dichotomy: "precious" versus "semi-precious." This distinction, predictably, has been mimicked in various forms across cultures, demonstrating a persistent human need to categorize and rank. In contemporary usage, the exclusive club of "precious stones" consists of [emerald](/Emerald), [ruby](/Ruby), [sapphire](/Sapphire), and [diamond](/Diamond). Every other gemstone, regardless of its individual merits or market value, is unceremoniously relegated to the "semi-precious" bin.

This historical segregation was, quite transparently, a reflection of the stones' perceived rarity in ancient times, coupled with certain inherent qualities. The chosen few were all notably [translucent](/Translucent), possessed captivating [color](/Color) in their purest forms (a notable exception being the naturally colorless [diamond](/Diamond)), and, crucially, exhibited exceptional hardness, scoring an impressive 8 to 10 on the rather quaint [Mohs scale of mineral hardness](/Mohs_scale_of_mineral_hardness). One might infer that humans, even then, appreciated things that resisted immediate destruction, a trait often lacking in their own endeavors.

However, this traditional distinction is, to put it mildly, often irrelevant in the modern market. It fails to account for contemporary values and discoveries. For instance, while the common [garnet](/Garnet) may be relatively inexpensive, a particularly vibrant green variety known as [tsavorite](/Tsavorite) can easily eclipse the value of a mediocre [emerald](/Emerald). The very notion of "precious" and "semi-precious" in a commercial context is inherently misleading, implying a fixed hierarchy of worth that simply doesn't exist when market forces and individual characteristics truly come into play. While it might broadly hint at desirability, it certainly doesn't guarantee actual market value. Another archaic, yet still referenced, term for "semi-precious" gemstones, particularly within the realms of [art history](/Art_history) and [archaeology](/Archaeology), is [hardstone](/Hardstone)—a term that at least accurately describes a physical property, rather than an arbitrary social construct of value.

In more enlightened, or at least more technically precise, modern times, [gemologists](/Gemology) are the arbiters of gemstone identity. They employ a rigorous framework of [technical terminology](/Technical_terminology) specific to the discipline of [gemology](/Gemology) to meticulously describe each gem's unique characteristics. The foundational identifier for any gemstone is its fundamental [chemical composition](/Chemical_composition). For example, a [diamond](/Diamond) is, rather elegantly, pure [carbon](/Carbon) (C), while the vibrant [sapphires](/Sapphire) and [rubies](/Ruby)—despite their wildly different hues—share the same base: [aluminium oxide](/Aluminium_oxide) (Al₂O₃). Many gems, being crystalline structures, are further categorized by their distinct [crystal system](/Crystal_system), which dictates their internal atomic arrangement, leading to classifications such as [cubic](/Cubic_crystal_system), [trigonal](/Trigonal), or [monoclinic](/Monoclinic). Beyond the internal structure, the external form a gem typically assumes in nature is referred to as its [crystal habit](/Crystal_habit). Diamonds, for instance, despite their cubic internal system, are frequently unearthed as striking [octahedrons](/Octahedron).

Gemstones are further organized into hierarchical layers of classification: distinct *groups*, then *species*, and finally *varieties*. Consider the example of [corundum](/Corundum). If it presents in a vivid red, it is specifically designated as a [ruby](/Ruby). Any other color of [corundum](/Corundum)—be it blue, yellow, or pink—is simply, and perhaps less dramatically, termed a [sapphire](/Sapphire). The mineral [beryl](/Beryl) offers another excellent illustration of this varietal diversity, encompassing [emerald](/Emerald) (green), [aquamarine](/Aquamarine_(gem)) (blue), the exceedingly rare [red beryl](/Red_beryl) (red), [goshenite](/Goshenite) (colorless), [heliodor](/Heliodor) (yellow), and [morganite](/Morganite) (pink). Each a distinct manifestation of the same underlying mineralogical blueprint.

The detailed characterization of gems delves into a multitude of properties, each contributing to its unique profile. These include the nuances of its [color](/Color) (analyzed by hue, tone, and saturation), any observable [optical phenomena](/Optical_phenomena), its surface [luster](/Lustre_(mineralogy)), its [refractive index](/Refractive_index) (how light bends as it passes through), [birefringence](/Birefringence) (the double refraction of light), [dispersion](/Dispersion_(optics)) (the 'fire' or spectral separation of light), [specific gravity](/Specific_gravity) (its density relative to water), its inherent [hardness](/Hardness_comparison), the way it tends to break along planes of weakness ([cleavage](/Cleavage_(crystal))), and the manner in which it breaks irregularly ([fracture](/Fracture)). Beyond these, some gems display more exotic traits like [pleochroism](/Pleochroism) (appearing to be different colors when viewed from different angles) or [double refraction](/Double_refraction), a property where light splits into two rays. The presence of [luminescence](/Luminescence) (glowing under UV light) and a distinct [absorption spectrum](/Absorption_spectrum) also provide critical clues for identification.

A rather poetic, if somewhat imprecise, traditional metric for a gem's quality is its "water." This term is employed to grade the stone's [luster](/Lustre_(mineralogy)), its overall transparency, or its perceived "brilliance." Gems of exceptional transparency and clarity are bestowed the honorific of "[first water](/First_water)," a testament to their pristine quality. Those of lesser transparency, perhaps harboring minor imperfections, are then relegated to "second" or "third water." It’s a quaint measure, hinting at the purity of a mountain spring, but ultimately less scientific than the technical analyses. Furthermore, the presence of internal material or structural imperfections, known as [inclusions](/Inclusion_(mineral)), often provides a unique fingerprint, hinting at the stone's natural formation history—or, for the less discerning, simply a flaw.

## Value

Spanish [emerald](/Emerald) and gold pendant at [Victoria and Albert Museum](/Victoria_and_Albert_Museum)
Enamelled gold, [amethyst](/Amethyst), and [pearl](/Pearl) pendant, about 1880, Pasquale Novissimo (1844–1914), V&A Museum number M.36-1928

The concept of "value" in gemstones is, much like most human constructs, a rather fluid and subjective affair, lacking any truly universally accepted grading system. The glaring exception, of course, is [diamond](/Diamond), which benefits from a meticulously crafted framework developed by the [Gemological Institute of America](/Gemological_Institute_of_America) (GIA) in the early 1950s. This system, a triumph of standardization, notably introduced the rather revolutionary concept of 10x magnification as the benchmark for assessing [clarity](/Clarity). For virtually all other gemstones, however, the assessment of value remains a more primitive exercise, relying on the naked eye—specifically, an assumed 20/20 vision—a testament to the enduring, if somewhat unreliable, human element in valuation.

To simplify the complex process of diamond assessment, a convenient [mnemonic device](/Mnemonic_device) was coined: the "four Cs"—[color](/Color), [cut](/Diamond_cut), [clarity